&lt;p&gt;The Arctic is undergoing rapid transition, with profound changes in sea ice, temperature, and environmental conditions. This change accelerating, leading to an Arctic Ocean with little summer sea ice and drastically altered sea ice properties in winter. These sea ice changes are causing major shifts in the fate and transport of pollutants in this region and feedbacks to climate. The Arctic region has a unique atmospheric chemistry; for example, the production of halogen oxidizers from sea salts lead to the seasonal depletion of ground-level ozone (O3) and the deposition of mercury onto sea ice, seawater and land. The uptake of atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) by seawater, controlled by the presence of sea ice, causes acidification of the waters and decreases the concentration of CO2 in the air. This project analyzed data collected by the O-Buoy Chemical Network project to measure atmospheric chemicals (bromine oxide - BrO, O3, CO2, other halogen gases), meteorology, and sea-ice properties; it was previously funded by the NSF OPP Arctic Observing Network. That project deployed fifteen (15) autonomous buoys (Figure 1) across the Arctic Ocean from 2009-2016, giving detailed, high time-resolution data relevant to understanding the Arctic atmosphere's chemistry in relation to sea ice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Our analysis shows that the atmospheric CO2 analysis over sea ice made by the O-Buoys was not different in from similar measurements made at Arctic coastal stations, with a similar seasonal signal and similar interannual increase in CO2 concentration over the study period. The use of the atmospheric transport model GEOS-Chem is helping explain regional and sub-seasonal differences among the observation sites; for example, the amplitude of the CO2 seasonal cycle is smaller over sea ice than at Arctic coastal stations, a reversal of the global pattern of increasing seasonal CO2 amplitude with latitude. In addition, there are several winter periods when the coastal stations and the nearest ice-tethered O-Buoys consistently differ from each other. The model is also helping to determine the source of the air containing CO2 arriving at each of the measurement sites, both over the coast and over sea ice. Model simulations also now reproduce some, but not all, events with high BrO observed by the O-Buoys, by including in the model a better spatial resolution of blowing saline snow sources (over sea ice) and a source of bromine from the snowpack as a function of O3 deposition onto the snow. Ongoing work with the model is comparing simulated CO2 fluxes with satellite CO2 observations and differences in the seasonality of BrO cycling between simulated results and observations. A last activity will be the synthesis of results and simulation of future scenarios using the GEOS-Chem model to indicate the impacts of halogen chemistry and CO2 exchange in a reduced sea ice world.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This project supported 2 PhD students (AK, FL, 1 female, 1 male), 1 undergraduate student (FL, 1 female) and 1 Research Experience for Undergraduates student (ME, 1 female). The Co-Investigators have participated in numerous national and international science committees, and have shared results at multiple local K-12 schools and community events. The Co-PIs and/or the graduate students have presented results at scientific conferences and workshops. The O-Buoy data are openly available at http://arcticdata.io.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Humankind, including scientists, needs to improve our understanding of the relevant processes controlling atmospheric chemistry and resulting air quality over the Arctic (including the Arctic Ocean) in order to make future global climate predictions with confidence that include Arctic atmospheric processes. Our analyses enabled scientific progress from NSF's investment in the novel and highly successful O-Buoy ice-tethered observational efforts.&lt;/p&gt; 

